<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-solving-quadratic-equations" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Solving Quadratic Equations</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.0 Numbers and Algebra
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.3 Quadratic Expressions and Equations
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p>
                        Solve quadratic equations by factorisation
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
            <p component="lesson-plan">
                <p> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Understand that the roots of a quadratic equation are the values of <m>x</m> that satisfy the equation, and that factorisation converts <m>ax^2 + bx + c = 0</m> into the form <m>(x + p)(x + q) = 0</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Factor quadratic expressions by finding two numbers whose product equals <m>c</m> (or <m>ac</m>) and whose sum equals <m>b</m>, then apply the Zero Product Property to solve for <m>x</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Use factorisation to solve real-world problems involving quadratic equations, such as finding dimensions of a garden, determining time values, and forming equations from word problems.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/numbers-and-algebra/quadratic-expressions-and-equations/solving-quadratic-equations.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/numbers-and-algebra/quadratic-expressions-and-equations/step-by-step-guide_solving-quadratic-equations.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To activate prior knowledge about factorisation and explore how to find the roots of a quadratic equation.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Learning Experience</title>
                <p>
                    <alert>Group Factorisation Challenge.</alert> Learners work in groups of 4<ndash/>5. Find the roots of the following equations using factorisation:
                    <ol marker="(i)">
                        <li><m>x^2 - 5x + 6 = 0</m></li>
                        <li><m>x^2 + 7x + 10 = 0</m></li>
                    </ol>
                    After solving, groups discuss: the steps followed, how the roots relate to the factors, and whether different methods were used. Each group shares their solutions and methods with the class.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    The teacher circulates among the groups, asking probing questions such as: <q>What two numbers multiply to give the constant term?</q>, <q>What do they add to?</q>, <q>How do you find <m>x</m>?</q>, <q>Can you verify your answer by substitution?</q>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Expected Outcomes</title>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(i)">
                        <li><m>(x - 2)(x - 3) = 0 \Rightarrow x = 2 \text{ or } x = 3</m></li>
                        <li><m>(x + 2)(x + 5) = 0 \Rightarrow x = -2 \text{ or } x = -5</m></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity xml:id="auto_9jwu39hn">
    <p xml:id="auto_is5r0so8">
        <em><term>Work in Groups.</term></em>
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_o678p0yf">
        Find the roots of the equation using factorization.
        <ol xml:id="auto_2s3uf3hd" marker="(i).">
            <li xml:id="auto_62fw5oe5">
                <p xml:id="auto_cqgldvnu"><m>x^2 - 5x + 6 = 0</m>.</p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_ic3swvf1">
                <p xml:id="auto_m9nkpj7u"><m>x^2 + 7x + 10 = 0</m>.</p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_rnn09z4g">
        After solving the equations, discuss the following:
        <ul xml:id="auto_yvido7h7">
            <li xml:id="auto_9ksk5kac">
                <p xml:id="auto_wzorkkpd">What steps did you follow in factorizing the quadratic equation?</p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_4ux0ps5w">
                <p xml:id="auto_3a7xce1o">How do the roots relate to the factors of the quadratic equation?</p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_tx7dxob4">
                <p xml:id="auto_ih6ilajw">Did any group use a different method to factorize the equation? Compare approaches.</p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_uwcc3wsr">
        Finally, each group will share their solved quadratic equations and the methods they used infront of the classroom.
    </p>
</activity>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formalize the definition of roots/solutions and the method for solving quadratic equations by factorisation.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Key Takeaways &amp; Teacher Connection</title>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Roots/Solutions:</alert> The numbers that satisfy a quadratic equation are called its <em>roots</em>. Once factored into <m>(x + p)(x + q) = 0</m>, set each factor equal to zero to solve.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>The 4-Step Method:</alert>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Step 1: Write in standard form <m>ax^2 + bx + c = 0</m>.</li>
                            <li>Step 2: Find two numbers <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> such that <m>m \times n = c</m> (or <m>ac</m>) and <m>m + n = b</m>.</li>
                            <li>Step 3: Rewrite and factor: <m>(x + m)(x + n) = 0</m>.</li>
                            <li>Step 4: Apply the Zero Product Property: set each factor equal to zero and solve.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Addressing Misconceptions:</alert> <q>Remember: <m>(x + 2) = 0</m> gives <m>x = -2</m>, NOT <m>x = 2</m>. Solving <m>(x + p) = 0</m> gives <m>x = -p</m>.</q>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>
    <p xml:id="auto_p982ehso">
        In our previous sections we have discussed the form of a quadratic expression, 
        identities and quadratic equations; how to form quadratic equations and differentiate between an expression and equation
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_y92h565p">
        In this section we are going to learn about solving the factored equation, 
        we are going to continue from the point where we form  factored equation
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_h9161zo3">
        Numbers that satisfy an equation (its solutions) are called the <em><term>roots</term></em> of the equation. 
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_xib6zowd">
        Once you have factored the quadratic into the form;
          <md>
             <mrow>(x+p)(x+q) \amp = 0 </mrow>
         </md>
        Set each factor equal to zero and solve for <m>x</m>:        
    </p>
    <sidebyside>
        <p xml:id="auto_63x8g4lg">
            <md>
                <mrow>(x + p) \amp = 0 </mrow> 
            </md>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_kdoha1uc">
            <md>
                <mrow> \text{or} \amp </mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_z3vxrby4">
            <md>
                <mrow>(x + q) \amp = 0 </mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
    </sidebyside>
    <p xml:id="auto_kzfcyelb">
        Solving these will give the two solutions for <m>x</m>.
    </p>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Practice and Application</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To apply the factorisation method to solve quadratic equations step by step.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Learning Experience</title>
                <p>
                    <alert>Worked Example:</alert> Solve <m>x^2 + 5x + 6 = 0</m>. Here <m>a = 1</m>, <m>b = 5</m>, <m>c = 6</m>. Find two numbers that multiply to <m>6</m> and add to <m>5</m>: these are <m>2</m> and <m>3</m>. Split the middle term: <m>x^2 + 2x + 3x + 6 = 0</m>. Group: <m>x(x + 2) + 3(x + 2) = 0</m>. Factor: <m>(x + 2)(x + 3) = 0</m>. Apply Zero Product Property: <m>x = -2</m> or <m>x = -3</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    The teacher walks through the example step by step, pausing to check learner understanding at each stage.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>
    <example xml:id="auto_mkxtaz7b">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_zrzcvxz9">
                
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_6644tjc1">
                Solve
                <md>
                    <mrow>x^2 + 5x + 6 \amp = 0 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_aj0tw3gm">
                Look for two numbers that if multiplied by <m>6</m> and when added up gives <m>5</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_x1wb3uth">
                These numbers are <m>2</m> and <m>3.</m> So we can write the equation as:
                <md>
                    <mrow>x^2 + 2x + 3x + 6 \amp = 0 </mrow>
                </md>
                Finding a common factor we have:
                <md>
                    <mrow>x(x + 2) + 3(x + 2) \amp = 0 </mrow>
                </md>
                Grouping we have th factors of the equation as:
                <md>
                    <mrow>(x +2) (x + 3) \amp = 0 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_nwoiq0rw">
                Setting each factor equal to zero (0).
            </p>
            <sidebyside>
                <p xml:id="auto_lb9szcxi">
                    <me>
                        x + 2 = 0
                    </me>                    
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_3ol9lk7v">
                    <me>
                        \text{or}
                    </me>                    
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_76cplxua">
                    <me>
                        x + 3 = 0
                    </me>                    
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
            <p xml:id="auto_0hsprly4">
                Solving for <m>x.</m>
            </p>
            <sidebyside>
                <p xml:id="auto_5aqg7o66">
                    <me>
                        x  = -2
                    </me>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_vopc5d8f">
                    <me>
                        \text{or}
                    </me>                    
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_5tu4esv8">
                    <me>
                        x = -3
                    </me>
                </p>                
            </sidebyside>
            <p xml:id="auto_y20m8r8o">
                Thus, the solutions to the quadratic equation <m>x^+5x+6=0</m> are;
                <me>
                    x = (-2) \, \text {and} \, x = (-3).
                </me>                    
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example xml:id="auto_el0pwzfm">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_vg47bf6i">
                
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_edolep2y">
                Solve,
                <md>
                    <mrow> 6x^2 + 13x + 6 \amp = 0 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_6kl0b5i5">
                We need 2 numbers to form factors, which when;
                <ul xml:id="auto_ztol9o49">
                    <li xml:id="auto_setozos2">
                        <p xml:id="auto_2j2o2bgz">
                            Multiplied to <m>6 \times 6 = 36</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_kry9nfc9">
                        <p xml:id="auto_2vxpdixw">
                            Added up gives <m>13.</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_iydpcqhv">
                These numbers are <m>9</m> and <m>4.</m> So rewrite the middle part.
                <md>
                    <mrow>6x^2 + 9x + 4x + 6 \amp = 0 </mrow>
                </md>
                Grouping the factors:
                <md>
                    <mrow>(6x^2 + 9x) + (4x + 6) \amp = 0 </mrow>
                </md>
                Factor each group:
                <md>
                    <mrow>3x(2x + 3) + 2(2x + 3) \amp = 0 </mrow>
                </md>
                <m>\,</m>
                <md>
                    <mrow>(2x+3)(3x+2) \amp = 0 </mrow>
                </md>
                Set each factor eaqual to zero:
            </p>
            <sidebyside>
                <p xml:id="auto_yqsbbsyx">
                    <me>
                        2x + 3 = 0
                    </me>                    
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_1cl424g0">
                    <me>
                        \text{or}
                    </me>                    
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_hmq5fqmp">
                    <me>
                        3x + 2 = 0
                    </me>                    
                </p>
            </sidebyside>

                <p xml:id="auto_hrwto7ns">
                    Solving for <m>x.</m>
                </p>

            <sidebyside>
                <p xml:id="auto_iuan04n7">
                   <me>
                        x = -\frac{3}{2}
                   </me>                   
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_sh5s1r7s">
                    <me>
                        \text{or}
                    </me>                    
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_8vcbuejh">
                    <me>
                        x = -\frac{2}{3}
                    </me>                    
                </p>                
            </sidebyside>
            <p xml:id="auto_gk22jd22">
                Thus, the solutions to <m>6x^2 +13x+6=0</m> are:
                <me>
                    x = -\frac{3}{2} \, \text{and} \, x = -\frac{2}{3}
                </me>                    
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Assessment / Exit Ticket</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    5 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formatively assess individual learner understanding of solving quadratic equations by factorisation.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Learning Experience</title>
                <p>
                    Learners independently complete the following:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <alert>Factorisation Questions:</alert>
                    <ol marker="(i)">
                        <li><m>x^2 + 7x + 10 = 0</m></li>
                        <li><m>x^2 - 5x + 6 = 0</m></li>
                        <li><m>x^2 + 3x - 4 = 0</m></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <alert>Word Problems:</alert>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>A car's speed is represented by <m>4x^2 - 16x + 15 = 0</m>. Find the possible values of <m>x</m>.</li>
                        <li>The sum of a number and its square is <m>42</m>. Form and solve a quadratic equation.</li>
                        <li>Solve <m>3x^2 - 14x + 8 = 0</m>.</li>
                        <li>A garden's area is <m>56 \text{ m}^2</m> and its length is <m>4</m> m more than its width. Find the dimensions.</li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Answer Key</title>
                <p>
                    <alert>Factorisation:</alert>
                    <ol marker="(i)">
                        <li><m>(x + 2)(x + 5) = 0 \Rightarrow x = -2 \text{ or } x = -5</m></li>
                        <li><m>(x - 2)(x - 3) = 0 \Rightarrow x = 2 \text{ or } x = 3</m></li>
                        <li><m>(x + 4)(x - 1) = 0 \Rightarrow x = -4 \text{ or } x = 1</m></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <alert>Word Problems:</alert>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <m>4x^2 - 16x + 15 = 0</m>: <m>ac = 60</m>, find <m>m + n = -16</m>, so <m>m = -10</m>, <m>n = -6</m>. Rewrite: <m>4x^2 - 10x - 6x + 15 = 0</m>. Factor: <m>2x(2x - 5) - 3(2x - 5) = 0</m>, giving <m>(2x - 5)(2x - 3) = 0</m>. Solutions: <m>x = \frac{5}{2} = 2.5</m> or <m>x = \frac{3}{2} = 1.5</m>.
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <m>x + x^2 = 42 \Rightarrow x^2 + x - 42 = 0 \Rightarrow (x + 7)(x - 6) = 0 \Rightarrow x = -7 \text{ or } x = 6</m>.
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <m>3x^2 - 14x + 8 = 0</m>: <m>ac = 24</m>, find <m>m + n = -14</m>, so <m>m = -12</m>, <m>n = -2</m>. Rewrite: <m>3x^2 - 12x - 2x + 8 = 0</m>. Factor: <m>3x(x - 4) - 2(x - 4) = 0</m>, giving <m>(3x - 2)(x - 4) = 0</m>. Solutions: <m>x = \frac{2}{3}</m> or <m>x = 4</m>.
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            Let width <m>= w</m>. Then <m>w(w + 4) = 56 \Rightarrow w^2 + 4w - 56 = 0</m>. Using the quadratic formula: <m>w = \frac{-4 \pm \sqrt{240}}{2} = -2 \pm 2\sqrt{15} \approx 5.75</m> m. Length <m>\approx 9.75</m> m.
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Collect and review the exit tickets to gauge learner understanding and identify any common misconceptions that need to be addressed in the next lesson.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>
    <exercises xml:id="exercises-quadratic-equations">
         <title>Exercise</title>
         <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_buwju945">
                    Solve the quadratic equation by factorisation.
                    <ol xml:id="auto_oppzhdup" marker="(i)" cols="2">
                        <li xml:id="auto_y1dhrkno">
                            <p xml:id="auto_vfi5sdu7">
                                <m>x^2 + 7x + 10 = 0</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_3xkfrdrs">
                            <p xml:id="auto_591dn2u3">
                               <m> x^2 - 5x + 6 = 0</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_0yoi4xgy">
                            <p xml:id="auto_i1a4ak21">
                                <m>x^2 + 3x - 4 = 0</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_z34pqjf0">
                            <p xml:id="auto_i5we4ynu">
                                <m>2x^2 + 9x + 7 = 0</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_nzdwwz34">
                            <p xml:id="auto_2hkstv6o">
                                <m>x^2 - 6x + 8 = 0</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="i)">
                        <li>
                            <p> 
                                <m>x = -5 \, \text{and} \, x = -2.</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>x = 2 \, \text{and} \, x = 3.</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>x = 1 \, \text{and} \, x = -4.</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>x = -1 \, \text{and} \, x = -\frac{7}{2}.</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>x = 2 \, \text{and} \, x = 4.</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
         </exercise>
         <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A car's speed is represented by a quadratic equation: 
                    <md>
                        <mrow>4x^2 - 16x + 15 \amp = 0 </mrow>
                    </md>. 
                    Find the possible values of x representing time.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>x = 1 \, \text{and} \, x = \frac{15}{4}.</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
         </exercise>
         <exercise>
            <statement>
                  <p>
                     The sum of a number and its square is <m>42</m>. 
                     Form a quadratic equation and solve it to find the number.
                  </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    Let the number be <m>x.</m> Then the equation can be written as:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>x^2 + x - 42 \amp = 0 </mrow>
                    </md>
                    Solving this gives:
                    <m>x = 6 \, \text{and} \, x = -7.</m> 
                </p>
            </answer>
         </exercise>
         <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Solve the quadratic equation:
                    <md>
                        <mrow> 3x^2 - 14x + 8 \amp = 0 </mrow>
                    </md>                                
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>x = 2 \, \text{and} \, x = \frac{4}{3}.</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
         </exercise>
            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        A garden's area is 56 square meters, and its length is 4 meters more than its width. 
                        Form and solve a quadratic equation to find the dimensions of the garden.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <answer>
                    <p>
                        Let the width of the garden be <m>x</m> meters. Then the length can be expressed as <m>x + 4</m> meters. 
                        The area of the garden can be represented by the equation:
                        <md>
                            <mrow>x(x + 4) \amp = 56 </mrow>
                        </md>
                        Expanding this gives:
                        <md>
                            <mrow>x^2 + 4x - 56 \amp = 0 </mrow>
                        </md>
                        Solving this quadratic equation yields:
                        <m>x = 7 \, \text{and} \, x = -8.</m> 
                        Since dimensions cannot be negative, the width of the garden is <m>7</m> meters and the length is <m>11</m> meters.
                    </p>
                </answer>
                </exercise>
            </exercises>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation</title>

        <table>
            <title>Differentiation</title>
            <tabular halign="left">
                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Learner Group</cell>
                    <cell>Strategy &amp; Learning Experience</cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Struggling Learners (Support)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Scaffolding:</alert> Provide a factor-pair reference sheet. Use color-coded steps for the 4-step method. Start with simpler equations where <m>a = 1</m> and <m>c</m> is positive. Allow use of multiplication tables for finding factor pairs.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>On-Level Learners (Core)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line>Complete all practice problems and exit ticket questions. Verify solutions by substitution. Work in pairs to compare methods and check answers.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Advanced Learners (Challenge)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Extended Learning Experience:</alert> Solve equations where <m>a \neq 1</m>. Create original word problems that lead to quadratic equations. Explore the relationship between the sum and product of roots: sum <m>= \frac{-b}{a}</m>, product <m>= \frac{c}{a}</m>.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Extension Activity</title>
            <p>
                A rectangular swimming pool has an area of <m>60 \text{ m}^2</m>. The length of the pool is <m>4</m> m more than its width.
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>Form a quadratic equation: <m>w(w + 4) = 60 \Rightarrow w^2 + 4w - 60 = 0</m>.</li>
                    <li>Solve by factorisation: <m>(w + 10)(w - 6) = 0 \Rightarrow w = 6</m> m, so length <m>= 10</m> m.</li>
                    <li>If a <m>2</m> m wide path surrounds the pool, find the total area: total dimensions <m>= 10 \times 14 = 140 \text{ m}^2</m>.</li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>
